            <h2>Minor Nouns</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">M</span>inor nouns, sometimes called minor declensions, can
                be split into three categories: u-declensions, r-declensions, and i-mutation declensions.
            </p>
            <h3>U-Declensions</h3>
            <p>The u-declension contains no neuter nouns, but even so, it declines based on vowel-length, not gender.
                Two-syllable words with a short-stemmed vowel, like '<em>sunu — son</em>',
                '<em>duru — door</em>', and '<em>medu — meadow</em>', decline one way, while one-syllable words with a
                long-stemmed vowel, like '<em>hond — hand</em>', '<em>weald — forest</em>', and '<em>feld — field</em>',
                decline another way.</p>
